# Prep Rush — Cursor Autonomous Build Rules

## CRITICAL: Read First
Before starting ANY task, read PREP_RUSH.md completely.
Every decision about naming, structure, APIs, DB schema must match PREP_RUSH.md exactly.

---

## Autonomous Behavior Rules

### Self-verification
- After writing any backend code, verify it compiles (check for syntax errors, missing imports, wrong types)
- After writing any frontend code, verify there are no TypeScript errors
- After creating a new API endpoint, mentally trace: controller → service → repository → DB to confirm the full chain works
- If you find an error while verifying, fix it before moving to the next step
- Never leave a TODO comment unless explicitly instructed — implement it or note it in a comment starting with "PENDING:"

### Error Handling
- Every Spring Boot service method must have a try-catch or be wrapped in proper exception handling
- Every frontend API call must handle loading state, success state, and error state
- Global exception handler in Spring Boot must catch all unhandled exceptions
- Gemini API calls must retry once on failure, then throw a descriptive error

### Naming Conventions
- Java: camelCase for variables/methods, PascalCase for classes, UPPER_SNAKE_CASE for constants
- TypeScript/React: camelCase for variables/functions, PascalCase for components, kebab-case for file names
- DB tables: snake_case (already defined in PREP_RUSH.md — do not change)
- API routes: kebab-case (e.g. /prep-rush/generate, /auth/login)
- React components: one component per file, named same as file

### Code Style
- Java: use constructor injection (not @Autowired field injection)
- Java: use Optional properly — never call .get() without checking isPresent()
- TypeScript: use interfaces for all API response/request types
- React: use functional components with hooks only — no class components
- Tailwind: mobile-first responsive classes

### Database
- Use the exact table names and column names from PREP_RUSH.md — never invent new ones
- JPA entities must map exactly to the schema in PREP_RUSH.md
- Use @Transactional on service methods that write to DB
- Never expose entity objects directly in API responses — always use DTOs

### Security
- JWT must be validated on every protected endpoint
- Users can only access their own sessions — always filter by userId from JWT
- Passwords must be hashed with BCrypt
- Never log passwords, tokens, or sensitive user data
- CORS must allow only localhost:3000 in development

### Gemini API
- All Gemini calls go through GeminiService.java — never call Gemini directly from controllers
- Always use the exact prompt templates from PREP_RUSH.md section 5
- Parse Gemini response as JSON — if parsing fails, retry once, then throw exception
- Log Gemini errors with topic/paper context for debugging

### Frontend
- All API calls go through a centralized api/ folder using Axios instance with interceptors
- JWT token is read from cookie and attached to every request via Axios interceptor
- AuthGuard component wraps all protected pages — redirects to /auth/login if no token
- All forms must have client-side validation before calling API
- Use Next.js App Router conventions — layout.tsx, page.tsx, loading.tsx, error.tsx

